      "text": "Many long-term smokers come to assume that low energy, afternoon slumps, getting winded easily, and waking up tired are just normal life — or just ageing. Often a large part of it was the smoking. Carbon monoxide and other compounds reduce how much oxygen your blood carries, so every muscle and organ ran slightly starved; the drug also disrupts sleep quality. As your body clears and your oxygen-carrying capacity recovers, a lot of people are genuinely surprised to feel more awake, more capable, and more up for things than they have in years.\n\nDon't dismiss this as minor. The return of energy changes what your days can hold. Stairs without stopping. A walk that's a pleasure, not a chore. Waking actually rested. Wanting to move. These aren't just health metrics — they're the texture of a fuller life coming back online."
